Amine de Babilonia ha interpretado una canci√≥n titulada "Choufou l'amour madarate fiya", que significa literalmente "Miren lo que el amor me ha hecho", con hermosas letras y sobre todo una hermosa melod√≠a digna de las mejores salsas cubanas. My dear Luis Fonsi, 

Amine de Babylone has performed a song titled "Choufou l'amour madarate fiya", which literally means "Look what love has done to me", with beautiful lyrics and especially a beautiful melody worthy of the greatest Cuban salsas. Bajaj Chetak.text:
Buy only base model for limited ride usage for home with tec pac
1.Low height helps people with height less than 5.6ft (my sister chose this model purely for this reason instead of ola)
2.Smooth acceleration wont cause dramatic experience which is great for daily use.
3.Range is enough for 3 Days if you have daily run of 15km. 
4. If you want ev just for adrenaline rush limited people using it for longer daily run, this isnt for you, go for Ola or Ather 
5. Its Totally a purpose driven scooter and not the one to travel city to city.
6. Service cost is same as ICE scooter but experience at service center is better than new companies like ola ather as Bajaj holds experience how to handle this part.


OLA have wide option to chose for from commute to long range now, only concern comes down to height of scooter and service factors which they'll need atleast 7years to improve.
Ather is sporty commited scooter costly but it justifies it with quality and service.
Iqube and Chetak is as same as other ICE scooter (if you use 2 to 3 liters of petrol every week as of now) we have seen in last 5 6 years but just in ev from experienced manufturers which.

First decide which fuel option suits you, ev need time to refuel petrol need maintenance with cost but less time consuming

Bajaj Chetak.text:
That video is the absolute bane of my existence, a true testament to the internet‚Äôs ability to take something utterly meaningless and turn it into an unstoppable force of chaos. It‚Äôs not just annoying‚Äîit‚Äôs a psychological weapon disguised as a harmless meme. The moment I see that stupid, flimsy, stick-like figure start wiggling, I already know I‚Äôve been played. It‚Äôs the ultimate troll move, a complete waste of time, yet somehow so effective that it‚Äôs impossible to avoid. There I am, innocently scrolling through videos, expecting some actual content, maybe a cool clip, an insightful fact, or literally anything of value, and BAM‚Äîsuddenly, I‚Äôm met with that jittery, lifeless stick insect doing its ridiculous little dance. It‚Äôs as if the universe itself conspires to make sure that no matter where I go, no matter how careful I am, I will always, always get stick bugged. The animation? It‚Äôs not even good! It looks like it was thrown together in five minutes by someone who had no intention other than to make people suffer. The movements are erratic, awkward, and just off enough to be infuriating. It‚Äôs like watching a marionette controlled by someone who has absolutely no idea what they‚Äôre doing. And don‚Äôt even get me started on the song. That awful, infuriatingly catchy tune that has no right to be as memorable as it is. It burrows into my brain like an uninvited parasite, looping endlessly, echoing in my mind when I least expect it. I could be trying to sleep, focusing on work, or even just enjoying a peaceful moment, and suddenly, the sound of that cursed song starts creeping in, haunting me like a ghost of memes past.
And the worst part? The fact that it works. Every. Single. Time. No matter how much I try to resist, no matter how much I mentally prepare myself, I always fall for it. Because the second you think you‚Äôre safe, the second you let your guard down, that‚Äôs when it strikes. It‚Äôs embedded into the fabric of internet culture, disguised in unexpected places, waiting to ambush unsuspecting victims like some sort of digital predator. Sometimes, it‚Äôs in a normal video with no warning‚Äîno suspicious title, no obvious bait, just a seemingly harmless clip before the dreaded moment arrives. Other times, it‚Äôs a part of a meme compilation, hiding in the middle so you don‚Äôt even realize what‚Äôs happening until it‚Äôs too late. And let‚Äôs not forget the absolute betrayal of friends who send a link with something like, ‚ÄúHey, check this out! It‚Äôs so cool!‚Äù only for it to lead straight to the cursed stick bug dance. It‚Äôs a never-ending cycle of trickery, frustration, and humiliation, and the internet loves it. The sheer audacity of this meme is what truly baffles me. It has no reason to exist. It adds nothing of value to the world. And yet, it has cemented itself in internet history as one of the most effective and annoying troll tactics ever devised. I can‚Äôt escape it. None of us can. It‚Äôs a force of nature at this point, an entity that thrives on deception and disappointment. I hate it. I respect it. And I hate that I respect it. No matter how much I despise Get Stick Bugged Lol, I know, deep down, that it will never die. It will keep lurking in the shadows, waiting for its next victim, waiting for me to drop my guard just one more time. And no matter how much I resist, no matter how much I try to avoid it, I know one thing for certain: I will always get stick bugged.

Ultraviolette.text:
Even if Ultraviolet offered me their EV bike for free with a bow on top, lifetime charging, service and upgrades...I still wouldn‚Äôt take it. Sell it to someone who likes tech toys. I ride machines not experiments.
Let‚Äôs get brutally honest here..EV bikes like Ultraviolet are flashy, over glorified gadgets. They look good on paper and Instagram reels but in real world Indian conditions? They're a joke! Our roads, weather, dust and distances don‚Äôt care about your digital dashboard or futuristic LED lights ü§∑üèº‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

My 11 year old Royal Enfield Classic 500 which they don‚Äôt even make anymore...still dominates rough terrains like Ladakh, Himachal, Nepal and the Northeast without skipping a beat. It doesn‚Äôt need an update. It doesn‚Äôt panic if there‚Äôs no charger nearby. It doesn‚Äôt beg for software support or battery calibration. It just rides and roars. Every damn time üëçüç∫ These EVs? They're built for urban coffee shop crawls and weekend flexing not for people who actually live and breathe adventure. Battery anxiety is real. Charging stations are still inconsistent. And once your battery degrades and it will in 2‚Äì4 years in India‚Äôs heat. You‚Äôre left with a useless, overpriced e-brick. And good luck finding a mechanic for that in the middle of nowhere üòÇ
You can cover the whole of India with charging stations and I still won‚Äôt trade a real engine for a silent spin. Torque, reliability, control and soul that‚Äôs what makes a bike a machine. Not circuits and Bluetooth. So no I don‚Äôt want Ultraviolet, even for free ü§∑üèº‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è I want a bike that bleeds character, not a plastic spaceship with a progress bar üëç

Ultraviolette.text:
Urban company is the worst. I live in a metro city. I ordered native m1 on 19th , it got delivered on 21st. It was supposed to be installed on 22nd. After waiting for long period for so called "professional" to attend calls , he informed me that he had taken leave for the day for some reason. So the day of 22nd is wasted and after chatting with a bot for long time in their pathetic app I finally got a call from their customer care who gave me assurance that it will be installed on 23rd. On the 23rd I called the professional to know if he is coming or not. Everything was fine till the scheduled installation time. On the 23rd also the professional didn't show up. After chatting with him , he told that he is with his family visiting someplace.  I have no option other than rescheduling for 24th. On 24th the professional came and opened the box and it shows that the product is a refurbished/used product having several scratches and dents on body. On 26th I got call from urban company,  they asked for the damage pics , which I uploaded. They recommend for replacement, but I asked for return of the product. They confirmed that product will be returned with in 3 days. Still no confirmation of the same or no one has showed up for the same.

The product may be good and service may be prompt for a lot of people.  
But for me it is a disaster. And I don't have faith on a company which fails to deliver their promisses multiple times. 
Don't buy this.
